  "prompt": "How do I prove that ((sinA) ^2) +1/ (sinA) ^2) ((cosA) ^2) +1/ (cosA) ^2)) \u226525/4?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, let's simplify the notation. Let's define:\n   \u2022 x = sin(A)\n   \u2022 y = cos(A)\n\n2) Then our inequality becomes:\n   ((x\u00b2+1)/(x\u00b2)) * ((y\u00b2+1)/(y\u00b2)) \u2265 25/4\n\n3) Rearranging:\n   (x\u00b2+1)/(x\u00b2) * (y\u00b2+1)/(y\u00b2) \u2265 25/4\n\n4) Key trigonometric identity: x\u00b2 + y\u00b2 = 1\n\n5) Expand the left side:\n   = ((x\u00b2+1)/x\u00b2) * ((y\u00b2+1)/y\u00b2)\n   = (1 + 1/x\u00b2) * (1 + 1/y\u00b2)\n\n6) Now, by AM-GM inequality, we know that:\n   1/x\u00b2 \u2265 1 and 1/y\u00b2 \u2265 1\n\n7) So, 1 + 1/x\u00b2 \u2265 2\u221a(1 * 1/x\u00b2) = 2/x\n   Similarly, 1 + 1/y\u00b2 \u2265 2/y\n\n8) Therefore:\n   (1 + 1/x\u00b2) * (1 + 1/y\u00b2) \u2265 4/|xy|\n\n9) But |xy| = |sin(A)cos(A)| = 1/2 sin(2A)\n   This is always \u2264 1/2\n\n10) So, (1 + 1/x\u00b2) * (1 + 1/y\u00b2) \u2265 4/(1/2) = 8\n\n11) And 8 \u2265 25/4\n\nTherefore, the inequality is proven.\n\nThe key steps were using AM-GM inequality and trigonometric identities.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any step?",
